postcontent: This pistol is a complete Radical Firearms 10.5" upper chambered in 5.56mm on a lower that I put together myself. This is the eaiest way to get a short SBR-like gun without the wait and cost of an ATF NFA tax stamp. Gun was function tested when I put it together two years ago and runs well. Only has about 250 rounds through it. The only reason I'm selling is that I've gotten an actual Colt 6933 SBR now so I will no longer need this AR "Pistol".See parts list below with current component prices if you were to build this today... it would cost over $675 to source all this before tax/shipping but I'll let it go for $550 total or best offer. I'm willing to meet up for a face to face sale or trade with someone in a public setting within about a 1 hour drive of Akron. Radical Firearms M4 Flat Top Forged Receiver, 10.5" Melonite 5.56mm Barrel, Free Float Quad Rail, Low Pro Gas Block, and A2 Hider ($280)Radical Firearms BCG is also Melonite Coated ($95)Twisted River Tactical Forged lower ($60)Toms Tactical Lower Parts Kit ($50)Sig SBX-15 Pistol Brace ($90)KAK Super SIG SB-15 Pistol Buffer Tube Kit with QD Endplate ($93)Included is ONE 30 round Pmag Magazine ($8)(OPTIONAL) Daniel Defense Fixed Iron Sights(OPTIONAL) Primary Arms MD-09 Microdot(OPTIONAL) ADM Mount For T1 Mocro allows for a lower 1/3 CowitnessTwo things:1) The red dot optic and iron sights in the photo ARE NOT incuded in the $550 price. If you want them the red dot will be +$80, the ADM T1 Micro mount is +$80, and the Daniel Defense Iron Sights will be +$120 ... or +$275 for all of the sights/optics together. I am quite firm on these sight and optic additional prices.  Again, the $550 price is for the flattop Rifle with one Mag only - optics and sights are extra.2) About 1-1/2 years ago, I attempted to change out the handguards. Radical uses a YHM-style barrel nut and float tube. It was so tightly installed at the factory that my barrel wrench could NOT remove it and some marring was caused to some of the barrel nut wrench holes. See Photo attached. The damage is limited to two spanner wrench holes on the barrel nut and is minor, it does not affect safety or function whatsoever, and is 100% NOT visible with the rail installed. I've shot many rounds since and it has not afected accuracy or function and does not prevent further attempts of removing the nut... although I'd reccomend a better armorers wrench than my 2-hole spanner before attempting again.

title: For Sale:  COLT 1911 USMC Mfg. 1916
postcontent: Colt Model: 1911 This is an example of a scarce and very desirable example of one of the 600 Model 1911 pistols shipped from Colt to the U.S. Marine Corps at the Philadelphia Navy Yard on November 27, 1916. The pistol has the standard Army markings. "MODEL OF 1911. U.S. ARMY" on the right side of the slide. "UNITED STATES PROPERTY" is marked on the left side of the frame in front of the trigger guard and the circled "GHS" monogram of Ordnance Inspector Maj. Gilbert H. Stewart is stamped above the magazine release. An "H" provisional inspection mark is stamped on the receiver near the disconnector hole, on the rear of the slide above the firing pin hole and on the top of the barrel chamber. The left side of the slide is marked with Colt's 1897-1913 patent dates in a two-line block followed by the two-line Hartford address and the Rampant Colt motif behind the slide serrations. The serial number is located on the right side of the receiver above the trigger. The barrel chamber has a "P" proofmark. The pistol has the military brush blue finish, two-tone magazine with lanyard loop and is fitted with checkered walnut grips with a diamond around the screws Serial Number: 151821 Condition: This Colt is 100% correct , 99% finish ,Professionally restored by Turnbull Restoration mint condition showing only the very slightest handling/storage marks.
